segments.text: whatever you can remember of your childhood, including the names of your parents, places and dates of birth and death if you know them, things of that nature, the schools you attended before going to college and something of that nature.
I was born in Nashville, Tennessee on July 16th, 1904.
My father was William Abbott, and my mother was Eleanor Ryan Abbott.
My father died when I was very young.
As I recall, it was 1910.
But my mother lived to be about 93 and retained her health, I'm happy to say, all of that time.
And she stayed on in Nashville, although I came to Texas and never left Texas after I did come here.
I came in 1926.
Now, before that, I attended the public schools in Nashville.
The grade school I attended from the first grade up to the eighth was called Howard School in South Nashville.
I think it may still be in existence, although I'm not sure whether it's an active school or not.
The high school I attended was Hume-Fogg, which at that time was the only high school in Nashville, although I think there was a county high school called Central.
Of course, now there are any number of high schools there, and I think it has become a special high school
I'm not sure what it does specialize in, but I think it is a special purpose high school now.
I went to, from there, I went to Vanderbilt and went five years there, the four undergraduate years and one graduate year.
Although I did not take my master's, I did have the graduate year in philosophy, but I was
already pretty sure that what I wanted to do was English language and literature, and I suspect that's why I did not finish the master's in philosophy.
Your undergraduate degree?
My undergraduate work was psychology and philosophy.
Was psychology and philosophy?
Yes.
Well, the department was a combined department of psychology and philosophy.
I suppose, technically, I was a philosophy major.
although I had as many psychology courses as were offered in the combined department.
Where does the English come in?
Was that a minor?
It was a minor and a very full minor, as a matter of fact.
I had about as many English courses as I had philosophy and psychology courses.
And, well, this may be of interest to some people.
I was in Vanderbilt.
At the time, the very famous fugitive group of poets was there, and while I was only on the fringe and attended only a few of their meetings, many of them were personal friends of mine.
Robert Penn Warren, and will I'm sure be known to most people, John Crowe Ransom,
who was a teacher of mine, and Walter Clyde Curry, a teacher of mine.
You notice they both are teachers in the Department of English, rather than in the Department of Philosophy.
The Department of Philosophy, as a matter of fact, was a one-man department.
It was Dr. Sanborn, who had been German trained, and was really a very fine person.
and an excellent teacher.
You mentioned this fugitive group of poets.
In what way were they a fugitive group?
I'm not sure what they were fleeing from.
Some of them called themselves unreconstructed southerners and a number of them were
of what they called themselves agrarians.
I'm not too sure of what they were, but also Jeffersonian in the agrarian sense.
But it was a happenstance that they all were either on the faculty at Vanderbilt or were students at Vanderbilt or were very closely associated with faculty and students.
at Vanderbilt.
Of course, a number of them went on to make international reputations for themselves, even when the fugitive group itself broke up.
I suspect our library has a full file of the fugitive, the actual fugitive poems.
Oh well, some others in the group were Alan Tate and
Oh, Wills, Ridley Wills, I remember, was in the group.
And Donald Davidson, I mentioned, I believe, Walter Clyde Curry was a member of the group.
Well, of course, that was very stimulating to students, and I'm not at all sure that it didn't influence me also to shift over into language and literature.
I was fortunate enough to...
and be elected to Fabio DiCaprio at Vanderbilt.
And at that time I was, and had been for several years, a counselor at a YMCA boys camp.
And it was at the camp that I received an offer to come to Texas A&M in the Department of English.
I went back to Vanderbilt and talked to my dean and asked him what I should do.
Texas seemed a long way off.
And he advised me to go and try, see whether I liked it or not.
So I accepted.
Had you applied for a position here?
No, no.
I suspect that my name, all from the dean's office,
was probably made available to a number of places, but I had not applied anywhere.
I was at the camp that summer when the offer came.
The amusing thing is that the offer was for $1,800 for nine months a year.
Three days later, I got an offer from the Citadel over in Carolina for $1,900.
And although $100 doesn't seem like very much, it did then.
But I had committed myself, and so I had to turn down the citadel offer.
And by way of coincidence, the man whose place I took at A&M, and this is, I'm sure, how Dr. Summey, Dr. George Summey, who was head of the department, I'm sure that's how he found out about me.
was Professor Bryce Harris, and when I got here, I discovered that he had taken the job at the Citadel that I had been offered, so our paths crossed.
He had been a graduate student at Vanderbilt a year ahead of me.
So you think it perhaps was on his recommendation?
I suspect so, yes, because Dr. Samuel would have had no way of knowing anything about it, and I had been in a
a couple of classes with Bryce Harris.
I was curious as to how a native Tennessean had arrived at College Station, Texas in 1925.
In 26.
And you've answered that.
You mentioned that Texas was a long way from Tennessee and you had some perhaps misgivings about going so far away from home.
What were your first reactions when you arrived in town?
Let me be sure that now I am being straightforward.

Actually, I think I started enjoying myself from the moment I landed, although it was on a very hot September day, and I had to walk from the railroad station to the old bachelor club where I had a room.
And I...
Met Bryce Harris there.
He had not left yet for the Citadel.
I met several of the people who were staying in the old bachelor club.
And I think I really started liking it almost immediately.
And while I originally had thought I might stay here for a year or so to get a little experience in seasoning, I never looked back.
For how long did you stay in the bachelor club?

I think about three years and then five of us who had been in the bachelor club rented an apartment at the north gate the apartments are still there at stucco building we rented an apartment and hired a cook to take care of us for two years let me see now if I can count up 26 I married in 31
So that would be the last two years before I married were with the five in the apartment.
And one of them is still here in retirement, Alvin Zeller.
Alvin Zeller, I think, was in our sanitary engineering department.
Now, he was in the apartment in the bachelor club with you?
Yes.
life like in a bachelor club, and what sorts of things could you do for...
Very, it was very pleasant.
It was also a boarding house, and while it was on college property, the dining room was run by a private person.
It was not a college, at that time it was a college,
not a college facility, but Mrs. Boyd ran the dining room.
It was an excellent dining room.
We all enjoyed it.
In fact, for a while, after we took the apartment, before we found our own cook, we still boarded with her.
And was this the Boyd family that had the store?
Yes, yes.
There's still some of the Boyds, a number of the Boyds still here.
They lived just across...
from the campus at that time.
I believe they had a store that was right across from about where the post office is, across the university's drive.
And so did the people who lived in the bachelor club then own the building?
No.
Or you rented it from the college?
No.
We rented a room.
Each individual rented a room.
I'm not sure how many rooms.
I'm guessing there must have been around 30 rooms in it.
It had been a wartime building, that is, World War I, but nothing, of course, is more permanent than a temporary building, and it was still there, still a sound building.
So the building was owned by the college?
It was owned by the college, yes.
And faculty members, I presume all faculty, they were all faculty members living there?
Yes, all of them were faculty members.
You mentioned about eating.
In the Bachelor Club, what types of things could you do for entertainment and recreation?
Oh, there was an almost perpetual bridge game going on every night.
And I remember that we had three or four dedicated domino players and a couple of dedicated chess players

and uh let's see what oh and a good many played golf where did you play golf at that point it was called the country club then it is the present brown municipal course any any other kind of physical activities other than golf that uh yes i uh
My sport, if I can be said to have had a sport, was tennis.
And I played a great deal of tennis.
I was fortunate enough to have as a friend the then coach of tennis, who was a member of the Department of English, Mr. William Thomas.
And so he would let me play with team members.
And, of course, I thoroughly enjoyed that.
And as a matter of fact, when Mr. Thomas died in 1935, very suddenly, I took over as coach, and I coached the tennis team then until I went off to Iowa to do complete work on my doctorate.
That was about three years.
At that time, did you have any, say, when you went to coach tennis,
Did you have any reduction in your teaching load, or did you get additional pay for coaching?
Never dreamed of asking.
It was just fun.
It was fun.
You got to play tennis along with the team members then when you coached.
Okay.
You mentioned that in 31 you married.
Did you then move on to the campus in a faculty home, or where did you live?
For the first...

couple of months or so we lived in that same apartment house an apartment became vacant and we lived in it but but we had been building our own home a little home out in college park it's the home we have now it was not ready when we married because they'd been very bad weather that fall it was supposed to have been ready when we married on the 23rd of december but it was not ready
for several weeks after that.
We lived in an apartment.
We were lucky enough to get this apartment for that time.
But at that point a goodly number of the faculty were living in houses on the campus, were they not?
A good many were living, particularly senior members of the faculty, were living on campus.
So then you've lived in the same residence from
Early 32, I take it, until today.
Until today, yeah.
You came here as an instructor from Vanderbilt in 26.
And you taught English.
Do you remember what courses you taught at that point?
Almost exclusively freshman courses because for many, many years, as I'm sure you know,

the department of english like history and economics and modern languages was a service department that is it we didn't even have majors for a long time much less candidates for the doctorate he existed to provide electives for the other departments so mostly freshmen but uh or maybe
one or two sections of a sophomore course.
And at that time, the loads were regularly 15 hours.
So you might have five sections.
I would have five sections.
And the chances are there would be three or four sections of freshman and one or two sections of sophomore.
And freshman English then was somewhat like today, grammar, primarily?
Primarily.
And sophomores would be what, American literature?
No.
what I guess they would call today types, like the essay, poems, novel, and a play or two.
I think it would be probably called a types course.
So kind of an introduction to the various types of literature.
And then there was another sophomore course called argumentation, which was the first course was the literature of types course.
And the second semester in the sophomore year,
was argumentation.
And almost all students took the four semesters, plus a one-hour course in the senior year in public speaking.
And that was changed, of course, later.
But at that time, that was almost universal, that you could count on every Aggie having freshman English, two semesters of sophomore English, and one speech course.
One speech course.
In the senior year.
Well, perhaps that was when he needed it the most.
I believe you rose to the rank of assistant professor in something like three years.
Was that a normal period at that point?
Honestly, I don't know.
Then you notice there was a long gap.
A long gap before you made associate professor, but then only one year an associate professor up to full.
Yes, but I had nothing but a bachelor's degree at that time.
You mean?
See, I had had a graduate year, but I did not take my master's degree.
You came here with a bachelor's.
Yeah.
You mentioned leaving here to go to Iowa for a graduate to work on your doctorate.
What year was that?
So that was shortly before you rose to the associate professor.
Yeah, and I got my degree in 39.
Uh-huh.
And had you been taking summer courses?
I had taken summer courses one summer at...
The University of Wisconsin at Madison and another at Tulane in New Orleans.
And then you had one full year at... And one full year at Vanderbilt before I came.
Oh, you mean at Iowa.
Well, I took leave for the academic year 1937-38.
I came back
for the year 38-39 but went up there in the summer and finished up in the summer of 39.
So in a sense you went uh you never did receive a master's degree then.
Never did.
Just went from the bachelor's and one year of graduate school then on into a doctorate program.
Not not very many places would allow you to do that today I would think.
Uh not many people do it.
I don't know how many places would uh
Say you can't do it.
I think most people like to have a crack at you at a master's term.
Well, now... And if you can make it, then they let you go on for a doctorate.
Well, I had to take the qualifying examination, which would have been the same thing as you would have done if you had the master's.
I didn't just say start out and go on to the doctorate.
You had a qualifying examination.
This was at Iowa.
Yes.
And you took that, what, after you'd already had two summers elsewhere, I take it?
Yes.
Now, the graduate college at Iowa was very, very considerate, and the graduate college did let me take my final examinations
much earlier than would be normal.
And I'm sure that very few universities would do it.
But the then dean of the graduate college who was started later became, I think, president of the Consolidated University of New York and then Illinois.
And it was his theory that if I wanted to take the chance,
Well, he would let me take the chance, so I wanted to take the chance, and did, after only, I think I took it, I did take it, the summer of 38.
So I was in there barely a year when I took my final examination.
I believe today, I can remember when I had mine, I had to have taken a specified number of hours beforehand.
And there was really no way you could do that in one year.
I believe you mentioned that Dr. Sumi was head of the English department when you came.
Was he a pretty good man to work under?
One of the finest men I ever knew in my life.
For how long then did he stay on as head of our chairman of the English department?
You probably have more accurate dates than this.
It was a number of years until I think he just plain got tired of administration and asked to be relieved.
He did want to stay on with his teaching and did stay on and then
The one who followed him was also our head librarian at the time, Thomas R. Mayo.
Well, I've heard lots of people say lots of good things about Dr. Mayo.
They were both very fine people.
I think Dr. Summey inspired the kind of loyalty that you rarely find in an individual.
I know of no one who
served under him who would not say the same thing.

I think it was his marvelous character that, although he was himself an excellent student of language, and his book on punctuation is, I suspect, still the standard book, although Dr. Summey has been dead several years now, and his revised version of that book
or must be 15 years old.
But it is still, I think, the standard work on punctuation.

Over the years that you were in the English department and in various other positions, was there a discernible difference in relationship between, say, incoming faculty members and the department head, or did that...
Were the department heads continuing to stay close to all of their faculty members as the size of the faculty increased, do you think?
Or was there almost necessary, in a sense, separation because the departments became fairly sizable?
Well, they didn't become fairly sizable for a number of years.
In fact, the department was fairly stable.
I would say remarkably stable.
until the war years.
And that was when the growth began, tremendous growth, of course.
I remember that Dr. Mayo, I think, had to fill, I hope I'm not exaggerating, 12 or 15 positions for one fall.
And we had a little indigestion
at that time because we greatly increased the size of the department.
Of course, that bulge was short-lived because we didn't start our real growth for a number of years after that.
We went up to about 9,000, I think, immediately after the war.
Then we fell back down to, what, around six?
Something like that.
Something like that.
My memory is not that accurate.
And then we just slowly grew.
It's only within the last three or four years, of course, that we've had this... Really ballooned.
Almost an explosion.
I believe I had this right in 47, you were moved up to an assistant to the dean and head of the basic division.
What was the goal of the basic division?
Well, it was...
It was a necessity, as a matter of fact.
We simply did not have room on campus for all the freshmen.
I mean, for all students.
And so the decision was made in 47.
I did not go in 47.
But Dr. Harrington, M.T.
Harrington, who later became president and chancellor,
He was asked to go out and establish an annex in what had been the Air Force Base, around the Air Force Base, which is presently our research center, as you know.
And he did start it.
And it was the next year that I went, when he was asked to become Dean of Arts and Sciences, Dean Bolton,
who was the executive dean.
The title was dean of the college, but it meant executive dean, equivalent today, I think, of executive vice president, or academic vice president, probably.
Asked me if I would go out and take charge of the annex, and I did, and had a marvelous time.
And I was there myself only from 48 until December of
1949, when I followed Dr. Harrington as Dean of Arts and Sciences.
When he became Dean of the College, or the Executive Dean.
But for those nearly two years, I had a very fine time.
So, it was a
out of necessity for space.
Oh, yes.
At least a portion of the student body.
You were asking about the basic division.
It was not at first thought of really as the basic division.
It was just a way of taking care of students.
But the students did so well out there, the freshmen who were out there, did so well that it seemed a good idea to preserve the freshmen as a separate unit.
And this was done even when room became available on the campus again, and they were, the freshmen were moved.
You have a record of this.
I don't remember, was it 50?
When they came back to the campus, when the freshmen were moved back to the campus.
I don't remember right offhand what it was.
But then it became an administrative unit on campus, and...
at its director on campus, who was John Bertrand, who had succeeded me.
And the basic division then remained a working division for a good many years after that.
So it was a, it was kind of a special help
For freshmen?
Yes.
Even after it was not a physical necessity?
Yeah.
The freshmen were all administered in this.
That is, the grades were kept there, the counseling was done there.
Were they registered separately?
Yeah, well, actually they were, of course, after that first year.
They went with their major department, as they do now.
